Greet the user

let userName = 'Jane';
userName ? console.log(`Hello, ${userName}!`) : console.log('Hello!');


If userName exists, greet them with their name; otherwise, just say "Hello!".

Log the userâ€™s question

let userQuestion = 'Will I become a successful coder?';
console.log(`${userName ? userName : 'You'} asked: ${userQuestion}`);


Prints the question with the userâ€™s name if available, otherwise "You asked: ...".

Generate a random number between 0 and 7

let randomNumber = Math.floor(Math.random() * 8);


Correctly generates an integer for the eight possible responses.

Assign a response using a switch

let eightBall = '';

switch (randomNumber) {
  case 0:
    eightBall = 'It is certain';
    break;
  case 1:
    eightBall = 'It is decidedly so';
    break;
  case 2:
    eightBall = 'Reply hazy try again';
    break;
  case 3:
    eightBall = 'Cannot predict now';
    break;
  case 4:
    eightBall = 'Do not count on it';
    break;
  case 5:
    eightBall = 'My sources say no';
    break;
  case 6:
    eightBall = 'Outlook not so good';
    break;
  case 7:
    eightBall = 'Signs point to yes';
    break;
}


Perfect way to map random numbers to Magic Eight Ball responses.

Log the answer

console.log(`The Magic Eight Ball says: ${eightBall}`);

ðŸ’¡ Optional Improvements

Use an array instead of a switch â€“ shorter and easier to maintain:

const eightBallResponses = [
  'It is certain',
  'It is decidedly so',
  'Reply hazy try again',
  'Cannot predict now',
  'Do not count on it',
  'My sources say no',
  'Outlook not so good',
  'Signs point to yes'
];

let eightBall = eightBallResponses[Math.floor(Math.random() * eightBallResponses.length)];


Combine greeting and question logging:

console.log(`Hello${userName ? ', ' + userName : ''}!`);
console.log(`${userName || 'You'} asked: ${userQuestion}`);
